{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473036"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:03:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1758"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.17,0.03,0.27,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107468"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89948"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5901"},{"type":"tags","id":"11217"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107468"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of progressive weakness in both legs. He reports having diarrhoea two weeks ago following a school camping trip but has otherwise been well. He denies any bladder or bowel disturbance. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Examination of the lower limbs demonstrates normal tone, reduced power bilaterally (4/5), absent reflexes, and patchy sensory loss in his legs. The remainder of the neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood samples are sent for full blood count, urea and electrolytes, and liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to confirm the suspected diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebrospinal fluid analysis","Stool culture for Campylobacter","MRI of the brain","Nerve conduction studies","Spirometry"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (GBS), an acute inflammatory polyneuropathy often triggered by a preceding infection. The history of recent diarrhoea, progressive symmetric muscle weakness, and absent reflexes are classic features of GBS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrospinal fluid analysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation in this case. It is crucial to perform a lumbar puncture for CSF analysis to exclude other potential causes of acute paralysis, such as central nervous system infections or inflammatory conditions, and potentially also to confirm GBS itself. The typical finding in GBS is albuminocytological dissociation - elevated CSF protein with a normal white blood cell count. However important to note, the absence of this finding does not rule out the diagnosis. CSF protein levels are elevated in about 50% of patients in the first three days after onset of weakness, increasing to 80% after the first week. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStool culture for Campylobacter\u003C/strong\u003E might identify a preceding infection that triggered GBS, as \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/em\u003E is a common antecedent pathogen. However, this would not confirm the diagnosis of GBS itself, and the diarrhoeal illness occurred two weeks ago, making a positive culture less likely. While identifying the triggering infection may be of epidemiological interest, it does not contribute to immediate management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically necessary for the initial diagnosis of GBS. While MRI might show enhancement of spinal nerve roots in some cases, these findings are not specific to GBS and are not required for diagnosis. MRI would be more appropriate if there were concerns about a central nervous system lesion, which is not suggested by this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in confirming the diagnosis of GBS and determining its subtype. However, they are not typically the first-line investigation. Nerve conduction studies often show abnormalities later in the course of the disease and require specialized equipment and expertise. They are usually performed after the initial diagnosis is made based on clinical presentation and CSF analysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpirometry\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in monitoring respiratory function in patients with GBS, as respiratory muscle weakness can develop and lead to respiratory failure. However, it is not a diagnostic test for GBS and would not be the most appropriate next step at this stage. Respiratory function should be monitored closely in all patients with suspected GBS, but other investigations to confirm the diagnosis take priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with CSF analysis, management would typically involve supportive care, monitoring for respiratory compromise, and consideration of immunotherapy such as intravenous immunoglobulin or plasma exchange.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebrospinal fluid analysis is the initial investigation of choice in suspected Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome to exclude other infective or inflammatory causes.","Albuminocytological dissociation (elevated protein with normal white cell count) in cerebrospinal fluid is characteristic of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome but is only present in approximately 64% of cases.","CSF protein levels are elevated in only 50% of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome patients in the first 3 days, increasing to 80% after the first week."],"references":["Leonhard SE, Papri N, Querol L, Rinaldi S, Shahrizaila N, Jacobs BC. Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Dec 19;10(1):1\u201319. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41572-024-00580-4","Leonhard SE, Mandarakas MR, Gondim FAA, Bateman K, Ferreira MLB, Cornblath DR, et al. Diagnosis and management of Guillain\u2013Barr\u00e9 syndrome in ten steps. Nat Rev Neurol. 2019 Nov;15(11):671\u201383. Available from: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41582-019-0250-9","van den Berg, B et al. Guillain-Barre syndrome: pathogenesis, diagnosis, treatment and prognosis. Nature Reviews Neurology. 2014;10(8):469. Gale Academic OneFile, dx.doi.org/10.1038/nrneurol.2014.121."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89948"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89948","links":{